			<title>Starcraft II: Legacy of the Void</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78264-Starcraft-II-Legacy-of-the-Void&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 13 Nov 2015 05:19:25 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>I usually take my time with these, but I binged the heck out of this one. I thought it was pretty great. Each time they learn from the previous campaign and make the next one better. I even made my peace with the story. Either I got used to it, or they did a better job, because I actually liked it...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I usually take my time with these, but I binged the heck out of this one. I thought it was pretty great. Each time they learn from the previous campaign and make the next one better. I even made my peace with the story. Either I got used to it, or they did a better job, because I actually liked it this time. Well, mostly. <br />
<br />
It's got a prologue to set things up, a campaign focusing almost exclusively on the protoss culture, and then an epilogue that ties all of the previous campaigns together. I've seen some derision regarding this last part, but I actually liked it. I was disappointed at the end of the protoss campaign that there was nothing that really matched the epic finale of the first game, but the epilogue had that in spades. It was also the only part of the entire thing I even found marginally difficult (on normal).<br />
<br />
<br />
My one major criticism is the same one I had in the previous campaigns. You get so more cool toys than ever before, but since each missions is tailored to a very specific and unique objective, often involving introducing a new unit, you don't always have much reason to use most of them. Basically there are no filler mindless &quot;kill the base, heck kill 5 bases&quot; maps, and the game could really use a few. <br />
<br />
<br />
In Wings of Liberty you had a tech tree for units and in Heart of the Swarm you had a cool evolution mechanic with wildly different zerg strains. In Legacy of the Void you have two different new systems to customize your army with. First, you get to upgrade your mothership itself with interchangeable systems based on available energy. These give you different support abilities you can call down in battle. Second, you get to customize your army layout by choosing a different faction's variant for any particular unit function. You can have Zealots with an aoe or a charge, Void Rays with a long range beam or one that splinters off and hits multiple targets, etc. You can change all of the above at any time before embarking on a mission.<br />
<br />
<br />
Minor spoilers here, but much of the game consists of uniting different Protoss factions, two of which established in Starcraft and Brood War, two which were introduced in Starcraft 2 but were never really fleshed out until now. You've got traditional Aiur units, Dark Templar units, Robotic purifiers, and what basically amount to Sith Protoss. I'm not even kidding. I dare anyone to see these guys and not immediately think the same thing. While there are all very similar units, this practically amounts to having four different possible army variations within the Protoss race itself.<br />
<br />
<br />
Which is why it's unfortunate there isn't more space to play with them all. Though with custom maps that may change, you can't very well just take them all into skirmish maps. Luckily Blizzard added a new mode that may accomplish this. There is now a co-op mode for two players, featuring some of the kinds of mission objectives you see in single player. It wasn't clear to me what exactly this was until I saw a video of TotalBiscuit playing it. You choose a hero, so I assumed it was a hero based mode, but what choosing a hero actually does is determine what kinds of units are available to you, and which of the cooler single player upgrades you can eventually unlock.<br />
<br />
I say eventually because you have to level up your hero through playing matches. This is my one problem with the mode. It uses upgrades you would expect to get more or less by default as a carrot on the stick to keep you playing, and aside from portrait unlocks or achievements is probably the only thing to really strive for in this mode. Grinding out levels to unlock a unit or upgrade you can select at any time in a normal map is off-putting to me. Luckily I expect them to continue support for this mode by adding new heroes and new missions.<br />
<br />
<br />
Which brings me to my final topic. With the final campaign done, Blizzard has announced that they will continue support for the game in smaller mission packs that won't take as long to make. The first announced pack will focus on the ghost Nova. I've seen people complaining because all DLC is evil all the time, but I also remember the wait in between Starcraft 1 and Starcraft 2. Heck, the wait between these expansions was long enough. I see nothing wrong with this, even though I'm not sure three missions at a time will be that satisfying unless they plan some kind of rigid episodic schedule.<br />
<br />
I can't speak for multiplayer. It's not really something I come to these games for anymore. There is a new &quot;two-headed&quot; mode, but that's been done before. It might have been interesting to see in competitive play, but I think Dota has sort of eaten Starcraft's lunch on that front.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
